05332nam a22006855i 9780814723074DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147230747 a10.18574/nyu/9780814723074.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)546901  a(OCoLC)50745274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ76.25 7aPSY0160002bisacsh04a306.76/52211 aBohan, Janis S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConversations about Psychology and Sexual Orientation /cJanis S. Bohan, Glenda M. Russell. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction. The Conversation Begins -- tChapter 2. Implications for Clinical Work -- tChapter 3. The Best of Both Worlds -- tChapter 4. Who Do WeWant You to Be? -- tChapter 5. Don't Look for Perfects -- tChapter 6. Implications for Psychological Research and Theory Building -- tChapter 7. Bringing Psychology in from the Cold -- tChapter 8. Psychology of Sexual Orientation -- tChapter 9. Implications for Public Policy -- tChapter 10. Lesbian, Gay, and Bisexual Issues in Public Policy -- tAfterword -- tReferences -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPsychology's approach to sexual orientation has long had its foundation in essentialism, which undergirds psychological theory and research as well as clinical practice and applications of psychology to public policy issues. It is only recently that psychology as a discipline has begun to entertain social constructivism as an alternative approach. Based on the belief that thoughtful dialogue can engender positive change, Conversations about Psychology and Sexual Orientation explores the implications for psychology of both essentialist and social constructionist understandings of sexual orientation. The book opens with an introduction presenting basic theoretical frameworks, followed by three application sections dealing with clinical practice, research and theory, and public policy. In each, the discussion takes the form of a conversation, as the authors first consider essentialist and constructionist approaches to the topic at hand. These thoughts, in turn, are followed by responses from distinguished scholars chosen for their expertise in a particular area. By providing an array of comments and thoughtful responses to topics surrounding psychology's approaches to sexual orientation, this valuable study sheds new light on the contrasting views held in the field and the ways in which essentialist and constructionist understandings may be applied to specific practices and policies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBisexualityxPsychological aspects. 0aBisexualsxMental health services. 0aGaysxMental health services. 0aHomosexualityxPsychological aspects. 0aPsychotherapy. 0aSexual orientationxPsychological aspects. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Human Sexuality (see also SOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Sexuality).2bisacsh1 aBohan, Janis S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCass, Vivienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaldeman, Douglas C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIasenza, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Fritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmoto, Allen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Glenda M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.